<emphasis box="[995,1278,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="299">Remsenornis bonariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="6" pageNumber="299">
Despite the subjectivity of generic limits, the recognition of 
<taxonomicName authority="Piacentini, 2017" authorityName="Piacentini" authorityYear="2017" box="[949,1093,369,392]" class="Aves" family="Thraupidae" genus="Remsenornis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="298" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[949,1093,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="299">Remsenornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
brings more consistency to classification of the Thraupidae—either the traditional or the one proposed by 
<bibRefCitation box="[1028,1242,404,429]" pageId="6" pageNumber="299" refString="Burns, K. J., Unitt, P. &amp; Mason, N. A. (2016) A genus-level classification of the family Thraupidae (Class Aves: Order Passeriformes). Zootaxa, 4088 (3), 329 - 354." type="journal article">
Burns 
<emphasis box="[1101,1157,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="299">et al.</emphasis>
(2016)
</bibRefCitation>
, which I strongly support. Additional minor adjustments may still be proposed, but I believe we are close to a robust and—hopefully—stable classification of the tanagers.
</paragraph>
